{"type":"text","timestamp":1777215716736,"sessionID":"ses_235b0923dffe5TeBgkFVn9h65x","part":{"id":"prt_dca4f95d3001UwMCJNzIM48QX2","messageID":"msg_dca4f6fa5001aFlS0vVoD7kCfG","sessionID":"ses_235b0923dffe5TeBgkFVn9h65x","type":"text","text":"| Dimension | Event Sourcing | Traditional CRUD |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Consistency** | Eventual by default; strong ordering via event store. Event replay rebuilds state. Audit log is inherent. | ACID transactions, immediate consistency. Audit requires separate logging. |\n| **Query Performance** | Poor for ad-hoc queries. Need CQRS + read-side projections. Event replay is slow at scale. | Excellent — query current state directly via indexed tables. |\n| **Learning Curve** | Steep. Event modeling, projections, snapshots, CQRS, eventual consistency — all new mental models. | Flat. Familiar to any developer who knows SQL/ORM. |\n| **Scalability** | Excellent for writes (append-only). Read scalability via independent projections. Event store is a natural partition boundary. | Writes bottleneck on locking/contention. Reads scale via read replicas. |\n| **Ops Cost** | High. Event store + projection DB + snapshots + replay tooling + schema evolution. More moving parts. | Low. Single DB, mature tooling, well-understood backup/restore. |\n\n**Recommendation: CRUD** — Confidence: 85%  \n\nFor a standard order management system, event sourcing is over-engineered unless you need a full audit trail regulated by law (e.g., financial trading) or must support temporal queries (\"what was the order state on March 1st?\"). The ops cost and learning curve of event sourcing aren't justified for most order systems. Use CRUD by default; add an append-only audit log table if you need history. Reserve event sourcing for domains where the business value of replayable, immutable history outweighs the operational burden.","time":{"start":1777215716732,"end":1777215716732}}}
